## 🧱 Why Subnetting Exists — The Classful Problem

Old classful system gave fixed blocks + fixed masks:

| Class | Network Bits | Default Mask | CIDR | Hosts/Network |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| A | 8 | 255.0.0.0 | /8 | ~16.7M |
| B | 16 | 255.255.0.0 | /16 | ~65,000 |
| C | 24 | 255.255.255.0 | /24 | 254 |

**Problems this caused:**
- **Wasted addresses** — a university needing a few thousand IPs got a whole Class B (65K+)
- **Huge broadcast domains** — one broadcast floods the entire network, killing performance
- **No real hierarchy** — hard to logically segment a large org's network

**Subnetting = solution.** Borrow bits from the host portion to carve a big network into smaller, manageable subnets — like dividing a city into neighborhoods, each with its own local addressing.

