## 🧮 The Binary Mechanics

### AND operation (finding the network address)
```
   11000000.10101000.00000001.00001010   (192.168.1.10)
AND 11111111.11111111.11111111.00000000   (255.255.255.0 = /24)
------------------------------------------
   11000000.10101000.00000001.00000000   (Network: 192.168.1.0)
```

### Borrowing bits (extending the mask)

| Bits Borrowed | New Mask (binary, last octet) | Decimal | CIDR | Subnets (2ⁿ) |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | 10000000 | 128 | /25 | 2 |
| 2 | 11000000 | 192 | /26 | 4 |
| 3 | 11100000 | 224 | /27 | 8 |

### The Two Core Formulas

- **Number of subnets** = 2ⁿ, where *n* = bits borrowed
- **Usable hosts per subnet** = 2^(H−n) − 2, where *H* = original host bits (−2 for network + broadcast addresses)

**From a /24 (8 host bits):**

| Borrowed | Host Bits Left | CIDR | Usable Hosts |
|---|---|---|---|
| 0 | 8 | /24 | 254 |
| 1 | 7 | /25 | 126 |
| 2 | 6 | /26 | 62 |
| 3 | 5 | /27 | 30 |

