## 🏢 Practical Walkthrough — Small Office Segmentation Plan

**Given:** `192.168.5.0/24`. Need to segment:

| Segment | Hosts Needed |
|---|---|
| Workstations | ~30 |
| Servers | ~5 |
| Printers/IoT | ~10 |
| Guest Wi-Fi | ~20 |

### Step 1 — Host bits needed per segment
| Segment | Formula | Host Bits |
|---|---|---|
| Workstations (30) | 2⁵−2=30 | 5 |
| Servers (5) | 2³−2=6 | 3 |
| Printers/IoT (10) | 2⁴−2=14 | 4 |
| Guest Wi-Fi (20) | 2⁵−2=30 | 5 |

→ **Most demanding = 5 host bits** (drives the whole design)

### Step 2 — Pick the mask
- /24 has 8 host bits; need 5 → borrow 8−5 = **3 bits** → **/27**, mask `255.255.255.224`
- Creates 2³ = 8 subnets, 30 usable hosts each — covers every segment's need

### Step 3 — Assign subnets (magic number = 32)

| Purpose | CIDR | Network | Broadcast | Usable Hosts |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Servers | 192.168.5.0/27 | .0 | .31 | .1–.30 |
| Workstations | 192.168.5.32/27 | .32 | .63 | .33–.62 |
| Printers/IoT | 192.168.5.64/27 | .64 | .95 | .65–.94 |
| Guest Wi-Fi | 192.168.5.96/27 | .96 | .127 | .97–.126 |

**Remaining subnets 4–7** (`.128` through `.255`) → reserved for future expansion.

### Why this design is good
- **Reduced broadcast domains** → better performance
- **Enhanced security** → firewalls between subnets; e.g. isolate guest Wi-Fi from internal resources
- **Better organization** → devices grouped logically by function

