## ⚠️ Common Mistakes & Troubleshooting

| Mistake | Symptom | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| Wrong subnet mask math | Devices in same intended subnet can't ping each other | Recheck binary math; verify against an online subnet calculator |
| Assigning network/broadcast address to a host | Device can't communicate or drops intermittently | Confirm host IP isn't all-0s or all-1s in host portion |
| Overlapping subnets | Devices behave as if on wrong subnet; weird routing | Carefully list every subnet range before assigning; check no overlap |
| Miscalculating host count | Run out of IPs early, or way over-allocated | Recheck 2^H−2 formula, including the −2 |
| Incorrect CIDR notation | Invalid IP config reported | Confirm CIDR prefix matches actual mask (e.g. /24 = 255.255.255.0) |
| Ignoring future growth | Forced to re-subnet later, causing disruption | Reserve extra subnets/host space up front |

### Troubleshooting steps
1. Check IP config on the host: `ipconfig` (Windows) or `ip a` / `ifconfig` (Linux/macOS) — verify IP, mask, gateway
2. Ping the default gateway — if it fails, suspect local IP config or physical connectivity first

